In TypeScript, you can use type assertions to tell the type system that you know more about the type of a value than the compiler does. For example, if you have a function that returns a value of type `string | number`, but you know that it will always return a string in your specific case, you can use a type assertion to tell the compiler that it is actually a string:

```ts
function getValue(): string | number {
  // ...
}

const value = getValue();
const stringValue = value as string; // Type assertion
```

In this example, we use the `as` keyword to assert that the type of the `value` variable is `string`, even though the function may return a number in some cases. This allows us to use methods and properties specific to strings on `stringValue` without causing a compiler error.

However, it's important to note that type assertions should be used with caution, as they can lead to runtime errors if the assertion is incorrect. It's generally recommended to use type assertions only when you are confident that the value will have the asserted type, and when there is no other way to achieve the desired behavior.

Here is an example of a C++ program that reads a text file line by line and counts the number of occurrences of a specific word:

```c++
#include <iostream>
#include <fstream>
#include <string>

int main() {
    std::ifstream file("example.txt"); // Replace "example.txt" with the name of your text file
    if (!file) {
        std::cerr << "Error opening file." << std::endl;
        return 1;
    }

    std::string word_to_count = "hello"; // Replace "hello" with the word you want to count occurrences of
    int count = 0;
    std::string line;
    while (std::getline(file, line)) {
        size_t pos = 0;
        while ((pos = line.find(word_to_count, pos)) != std::string::npos) {
            ++count;
            pos += word_to_count.length();
        }
    }
    file.close();
    std::cout << "The word '" << word_to_count << "' occurs " << count << " times in the file." << std::endl;
    return 0;
}
```

